===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|right}}, {{m|enm|riȝt}}, {{m|enm|reȝt}}, from {{inh|en|ang|riht}}, {{m|ang|ryht}}, {{m|ang|reht|t=right}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*rehtaz||right, direct}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*h₃reǵtós||having moved in a straight line}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*h₃reǵ-||to straighten, direct}}. An Indo-European past participle, it became a Germanic adjective which has been used also as a noun since the common Germanic period. Cognate with {{cog|fy|rjocht}}, {{cog|nl|recht}}, {{cog|de|recht}} and {{m|de|Recht}}, {{cog|sv|rätt}} and {{m|sv|rät}}, {{cog|da|ret}}, Norwegian Bokmål {{m|nb|rett}}, Norwegian Nynorsk {{m|nn|rett}}, and Icelandic {{m|is|rétt}}. The Indo-European root is also the source of Ancient Greek {{m|grc|ὀρεκτός}} and Latin {{m|la|rēctus}}; Albanian {{m|sq|drejt}} was borrowed from Latin.

